article.description:
Antawn Jamison scored 26 points, including a critical 3 with 42.5 seconds remaining, and Golden State ended a
14-game losing streak against Seattle with a 94-88 victory Saturday night.
article.headline: Warriors snap 14-game losing streak vs. Sonics
article.linkText: Jamison helps Warriors end long slide against Sonics
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Antawn Jamison took it upon himself to end a Golden State losing streak that began when he was rookie. Jamison scored 26 points, including seven in the final 1:23, as the Warriors ended a 14-game losing streak against the Seattle SuperSonics with a 94-88 victory Saturday night. It was the Warriors' first win over the SuperSonics since March 19, 1999, when Jamison was a 22-year-old rookie on his way toward averaging 9.6 points for the season. He entered Saturday night's game averaging 21.8 points, and the victory over Seattle showed just how much the Warriors rely on their star forward. "With the game on the line, let me create something, because I have the confidence that I can hit the shot or find the open man if I have to,'' said Jamison, who made 10 of 18 shots. The game was tied at 86 with 2:13 to play after Seattle center Jerome James sank a pair of free throws. Jamison was fouled by Brent Barry with 1:23 to play, and his two free throws gave the Warriors back the lead at 88-86. The Sonics, working the ball around looking for a good shot, couldn't find anyone open and they turned the ball over on a shot-clock violation with 58.7 seconds left. On the Warriors' ensuing possession, Jamison made an open 26-foot 3-pointer with 42.5 seconds left. Trailing 91-88 with 7.8 seconds left, the Sonics had a chance to tie, but Ray Allen's 3-point attempt missed. On Friday night, the Warriors lost to Dallas on a 3-pointer at the buzzer. This time, they were more fortunate. Richardson got the rebound from Allen's miss and was fouled. He made the first free throw with 0.4 seconds to play. His second foul shot missed, and Jamison tipped it in at the horn. "I apologized to Antawn last night on the airplane, because we didn't go to him down the stretch against Dallas,'' Warriors coach Eric Musselman said. "Earlier in the year we had gone to Antawn a ton down the stretch. Tonight we did look for him on pick and rolls and let him get a mismatch. That was a huge 3 he hit for us.'' Jason Richardson added 24 points for the Warriors, who also had lost 14 straight to the Sonics in Seattle, last winning on March 6, 1995. Rashard Lewis led the Sonics with 28 points, but he had only four in the second half. Allen had 21, while Reggie Evans had 12 rebounds. A win would have pushed the Sonics into a tie with Golden State for 10th place in the Western Conference. Instead, the Warriors moved two ahead of Seattle and are now 3½ behind eighth-place Phoenix. "It was a weird game for us,'' Allen said. "It seemed as though we had control of it at one point. We didn't really get to the free-throw line, and we created a lot of tough opportunities for ourselves. In the fourth quarter, we have to get to the free-throw line. It's a disappointing loss for us.'' Although the Warriors didn't have their typical 100-point game, they played well enough by shooting 48 percent. Seattle struggled, hitting 42 percent. Lewis, coming off a 30-point performance Thursday night, missed his only shot in the fourth quarter. "They started double-teaming me a lot more,'' Lewis said. " I knew that would happen in the second half because, obviously, my shot was falling. I figured they would play me a little closer.'' The Warriors entered the fourth quarter with a 68-66 lead but had to play without Murphy, who bruised his right knee midway through the third quarter. For the second straight game, Lewis came out aggressive on offense. He scored 13 in the first quarter, making six of 10 shots. His 3-pointer with 5:12 to play in the first quarter started a 10-2 run that Allen capped with a 3-pointer, giving Seattle a 27-20 lead. Golden State led 46-42 with 1:49 to play in the half on a layup by Arenas. After a layup by Brent Barry, he made a steal and threw the outlet to Allen, who lobbed the ball to Lewis above the rim for a fastbreak dunk that tied the score at 46. Game notes
The Warriors' lineup of Jamison, Arenas, Murphy, Richardson, and C Erick Dampier has started each of their 66 games this season. ... Arenas had scored 20 or more points in each of his previous seven games. He had 10.
